Lunar and diel activity analysis

This vignette demonstrates the Bayesian analysis and ternary classification used in âThe moonâs influence on the activity of tropical forest mammalsâ (Bischof et al, submitted).

Load Libraries

We load the libraries needed to run the example.

library(nimble)

library(R.utils) 
library(reshape2)
library(dplyr)
library(Ternary)
library(coda)

Source additional functions

We load additional custom functions for processing MCMC output and making ternary diagrams.

source("functions.R")

Analysis 1: Diel and lunar activity

Define model

We use package nimble (de Valpine et al. 2017; NIMBLE Development Team 2020) for Bayesian model fitting. Here, we define the nimble model for analysis 1, which we use to determine the prevalence of apparent lunar philia and lunar phobia based among tropical forest mammals detected using camera traps. The model has two submodels, one to estimate multinomial probabilities associated with diel activity and one to estimate multinomial probabilities associated with lunar activity. Estimation is performed independently for each species. Note that the model does not include random effects, but is structured to accommodate them and the associated hyper-parameters. Hence the term âhyperâ in some parameter names.

modelCode1 <- nimbleCode({
  for (sp in 1:n.species) {
    for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
      beta0[sp, k] ~ dunif(-20, 20)
      eta.dot.hyper[sp, k] <-  beta0[sp, k]
      
    }
    
    eta.dot.hyper[sp, K] <- 0
    
    for (k in 1:(K.moon - 1)) {
      beta0.moon[sp, k] ~ dunif(-20, 20)
      eta.moon.dot.hyper[sp, k] <- beta0.moon[sp, k]
      
    }#k
    eta.moon.dot.hyper[sp, K] <- 0
  }#sp
  
  
  for (i in 1:n.records) {
    #----DESIGNATION OF ACTIVITY TO DIEL PHASES
    
    for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
      eta.dot[i, k]  <-
        eta.dot.hyper[species[i], k]
      exp.eta[i, k] <- exp(eta.dot[i, k] + offset[i, k])
    }
    eta.dot[i, K] <- 0
    exp.eta[i, K] <- 1
    
    Z[i] <- sum(exp.eta[i, 1:K])
    p[i, 1:K] <- exp.eta[i, 1:K] / Z[i]
    y[i, 1:K] ~ dmulti(p[i, 1:K], N[i])
    
    #----DESIGNATION OF ACTIVITY TO LUNAR PHASES/PERIODS
    
    for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
      eta.moon.dot[i, k]  <-
        eta.moon.dot.hyper[species[i], k]
      
      exp.eta.moon[i, k] <-
        exp(eta.moon.dot[i, k] + offset.moon[i, k])
    }
    eta.moon.dot[i, K.moon] <- 0
    exp.eta.moon[i, K.moon] <- 1
    
    Z.moon[i] <- sum(exp.eta.moon[i, 1:K.moon])
    p.moon[i, 1:K] <- exp.eta.moon[i, 1:K.moon] / Z.moon[i]
    y.moon[i, 1:K] ~ dmulti(p.moon[i, 1:K.moon], N.moon[i])
    
  }#i
  
  #----DERIVED VARIABLES
  
  for (sp in 1:n.species) {
    #---species-level parameters
    
    Z.dot.hyper[sp] <- sum(exp(eta.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K]))
    p.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K] <-
      exp(eta.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K]) / Z.dot.hyper[sp]
    
    Z.moon.dot.hyper[sp] <-
      sum(exp(eta.moon.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K.moon]))
    p.moon.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K.moon] <-
      exp(eta.moon.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K.moon]) / Z.moon.dot.hyper[sp]
    
  }
  
  for (i in 1:n.records) {
    Z.dot[i] <- sum(exp(eta.dot[i, 1:K]))
    p.dot[i, 1:K] <- exp(eta.dot[i, 1:K]) / Z.dot[i]
    
    Z.moon.dot[i] <- sum(exp(eta.moon.dot[i, 1:K.moon]))
    p.moon.dot[i, 1:K.moon] <-
      exp(eta.moon.dot[i, 1:K.moon]) / Z.moon.dot[i]
    
  }
  
})

Load input data

We load the file containing the various objects serving as input for the model.

load("InputData1.RData")

Fit the model

Here we fit the nimble model. We chose a low number of iterations in this example, for faster fitting.

|-------------|-------------|-------------|-------------|
|-------------------------------------------------------|
|-------------|-------------|-------------|-------------|
|-------------------------------------------------------|
|-------------|-------------|-------------|-------------|
|-------------------------------------------------------|
nimOutput1 <- nimbleMCMC(
    code = modelCode1,
    constants = nimConstants1,
    data = nimData1,
    inits = nimInits1,
    monitors = c("p.dot.hyper","p.moon.dot.hyper"),
    niter = 10000,
    nburnin = 3000,
    thin = 8,
    nchains = 3,
    samplesAsCodaMCMC = TRUE
  )

Process MCMC output

We process the output from nimbleMCMC for easier handling of the posterior samples.

Review traceplots

Generate and inspect traceplots to visually assess convergence and mixing of the MCMC chains.

parms<-c("p.dot.hyper","p.moon.dot.hyper")
n.chains<-3

x<-parms[1]
posterior.df<-lapply(parms,function(x){
  ins<-NimbleOutputCoda1$sims.list[[x]]
  dimnames(ins)<-list(NULL,species.info1$SpeciesName,NULL)
  out<-melt(ins)
  colnames(out)<-c("iteration",paste("dim",1:(length(dim(ins))-1),sep=""),"value")
  out$chain<-rep(1:n.chains,each=dim(ins)[1]/n.chains)
  out$iteration<-rep(1:(dim(ins)[1]/n.chains),n.chains)

  return(out)
})

names(posterior.df)<-parms

sp<-sample(species.info1$SpeciesName,5)

traceplot.ls<-lapply(posterior.df,function(x){
  ggplot(x[x$dim1%in%sp,]) + 
    geom_line(aes(x=iteration,y=value,color=factor(chain))) +
    facet_grid(dim1~dim2,scales = "free")+
    theme(legend.position = "none")
  
})

Determine activity categories

We can designate the posterior samples of multinomial probabilities according to the ternary categorization we chose for diel behavior (7 categories; see also Figure 2 in the article). Diel activity category is determined based on the position of each posterior sample in the ternary diagram; overall diel activity for the species is the most common diel category in the posterior sample.

Analysis 2: Relationship with nocturnality

Define model

Here, we define the nimble model for analysis 2, which we use to test the hypothesis that lunar phobia is positively linked with nocturnality in tropical forest mammals. This model has two submodels, one to estimate multinomial probabilities associated with diel activity and one to estimate multinomial probabilities associated with lunar activity. The species-specific probability of being active at night (estimated in the diel activity submodel) is used as a covariate (shared by all species) on the multinomial probabilities in the lunar activity submodel.

modelCode2 <- nimbleCode({
  for (i in 1:n.observations) {
    for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
      beta0[i, k] ~ dunif(-20, 20)
      
    }
    
  }#i
  
  for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
    beta0.moon[k] ~ dunif(-10, 10)
    beta.nocturnal[k] ~ dunif(-10, 10)
  }
  
  for (i in 1:n.observations) {
    #----DESIGNATION OF ACTIVITY TO DIEL PHASES
    
    for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
      eta.dot[i, k]  <- beta0[i, k]
      
      exp.eta[i, k] <- exp(eta.dot[i, k] + offset[i, k])
    }
    eta.dot[i, K] <- 0
    exp.eta[i, K] <- 1
    
    Z[i] <- sum(exp.eta[i, 1:K])
    p[i, 1:K] <- exp.eta[i, 1:K] / Z[i]
    y[i, 1:K] ~ dmulti(p[i, 1:K], N[i])
    
    #----DESIGNATION OF ACTIVITY TO LUNAR PHASES/PERIODS
    
    for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
      eta.moon.dot[i, k]  <-
        beta0.moon[k]  + beta.nocturnal[k] * p.dot[i, 3]
      exp.eta.moon[i, k] <-
        exp(eta.moon.dot[i, k] + offset.moon[i, k])
    }
    
    eta.moon.dot[i, K] <- 0
    exp.eta.moon[i, K] <- 1
    
    Z.moon[i] <- sum(exp.eta.moon[i, 1:K.moon])
    p.moon[i, 1:K] <- exp.eta.moon[i, 1:K.moon] / Z.moon[i]
    y.moon[i, 1:K] ~ dmulti(p.moon[i, 1:K.moon], N.moon[i])
    
  }
  
  #----DERIVED VARIABLES
  
  for (i in 1:n.observations) {
    Z.dot[i] <- sum(exp(eta.dot[i, 1:K]))
    p.dot[i, 1:K] <- exp(eta.dot[i, 1:K]) / Z.dot[i]
    
    Z.moon.dot[i] <- sum(exp(eta.moon.dot[i, 1:K.moon]))
    p.moon.dot[i, 1:K.moon] <-
      exp(eta.moon.dot[i, 1:K.moon]) / Z.moon.dot[i]
    
  }
  
})

Analysis 3: Activity shifting

Define model

Here, we define the nimble model for analysis 3, which we use to detect and quantify changes in diel activity patterns and total activity levels during periods with full moon. This model has two submodels, one to estimate total number of activity events and one for multinomial probabilities associated with diel activity. Both submodels include terms that contrast moonlit with moonlit periods. Estimation is performed independently for each species. Note that the model does not include random effects, but is structured to accommodate them and the associated hyper parameters. Hence also the term âhyperâ in some parameter names.

modelCode3 <-  nimbleCode({
  for (lp in 1:2) { #  lp: lunar periods (1=moonlit, 2=other)
    for (sp in 1:n.species) {
      for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
        beta0[sp, k, lp] ~ dunif(-20, 20)
        eta.dot.hyper[sp, k, lp] <-  beta0[sp, k, lp]
      }
      
      eta.dot.hyper[sp, K, lp] <- 0
    }#sp
  }
  
  for (sp in 1:n.species) {
    beta.moonlit.N.dot.hyper[sp] ~ dunif(-20, 20)
  }#sp
  
  for (i in 1:n.records) {
    beta0.N[i] ~ dunif(-10, 10)
    
    beta.moonlit.N[i] <- beta.moonlit.N.dot.hyper[species[i]]
  }
  
  for (lp in 1:2) { 
    for (i in 1:n.records) {
      #----DESIGNATION OF ACTIVITY TO DIEL PHASES
      
      for (k in 1:(K - 1)) {
        eta.dot[i, k, lp]  <- eta.dot.hyper[species[i], k, lp]
        exp.eta[i, k, lp] <- exp(eta.dot[i, k, lp] + offset[i, k, lp])
      }
      eta.dot[i, K, lp] <- 0
      exp.eta[i, K, lp] <- 1
      
      Z[i, lp] <- sum(exp.eta[i, 1:K, lp])
      p[i, 1:K, lp] <- exp.eta[i, 1:K, lp] / Z[i, lp]
      y[i, 1:K, lp] ~ dmulti(p[i, 1:K, lp], N[i, lp])
      
      #----TOTAL DAILY ACTIVITY
      
      eta.N.dot[i, lp] <-  beta0.N[i] + beta.moonlit.N[i] * (2 - lp)
      
      lambda.N[i, lp] <- exp(eta.N.dot[i, lp] + offset.N[i, lp])
      
      N[i, lp] ~ dpois(lambda.N[i, lp])
      
    }
    
    
    #----DERIVED VARIABLES
    
    for (sp in 1:n.species) {
      #---species-level parameters
      
      Z.dot.hyper[sp, lp] <- sum(exp(eta.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K, lp]))
      p.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K, lp] <-
        exp(eta.dot.hyper[sp, 1:K, lp]) / Z.dot.hyper[sp, lp]
      
    }
  }
  
  for (lp in 1:2) { #  lunar periods
    
    for (i in 1:n.records) {
      Z.dot[i, lp] <- sum(exp(eta.dot[i, 1:K, lp]))
      p.dot[i, 1:K, lp] <- exp(eta.dot[i, 1:K, lp]) / Z.dot[i, lp]
      
      lambda.N.dot[i, lp]  <-
        exp(eta.N.dot[i, lp])#--offset-adjusted value of lambda
      
    }
    
  }
})

  postd.moonless[sample(dim(postd.moonless)[1], min(n, dim(postd.moonless)[1])), idx, ]


TernaryPoints(coordinates.moonlit,
              col = adjustcolor("lightgreen", 0.1),
              pch = 19)
TernaryPoints(coordinates.moonless,
              col = adjustcolor("orange", 0.1),
              pch = 19)

In addition, we can plot the distribution of the posterior signifying the change in overall activity level (expressed in photographic detections) during periods with full moon.

#-----SHIFT POSTERIOR (TOTAL ACTIVITY)
temp <- NimbleOutputCoda3$sims.list$beta.moonlit.N.dot.hyper
dimnames(temp) <- list(NULL, unique(species.info3$SpeciesName))
postd.df <- melt(temp) %>% tibble()
colnames(postd.df) <- c("iteration", "SpeciesName", "beta.moonlit.N")
postd.df2 <-
  postd.df %>% group_by(SpeciesName)  %>% summarise(
    mean.beta.moonlit.N = mean(beta.moonlit.N),
    lci = quantile(beta.moonlit.N, 0.025),
    uci = quantile(beta.moonlit.N, 0.975)
  )
ordered.species.list <-
  as.character(unique(postd.df2$SpeciesName[order(postd.df2$mean.beta.moonlit.N)]))
postd.df$SpeciesName <-
  factor(postd.df$SpeciesName, levels = ordered.species.list)
postd.df2$significant <-
  ifelse(postd.df2$lci > 0,
         "positive",
         ifelse(postd.df2$uci < 0, "negative", "not significant"))
postd.df_betaNmoon <- left_join(postd.df, postd.df2)


temp <-
  postd.df_betaNmoon$beta.moonlit.N[postd.df_betaNmoon$SpeciesName %in% sp]

this.dens <-
  density(postd.df_betaNmoon$beta.moonlit.N[postd.df_betaNmoon$SpeciesName %in%
                                               sp])
dens.df <- tibble(x = this.dens$x, y = this.dens$y)
dens.pos.df <- dens.df[dens.df$x > 0, ]
dens.neg.df <- dens.df[dens.df$x < 0, ]

poly.pos <- cbind(xx = c(dens.pos.df$x, rev(dens.pos.df$x))
                  ,
                  yy = c(dens.pos.df$y, rep(0, length(dens.pos.df$y))))

poly.neg <- cbind(xx = c(dens.neg.df$x, rev(dens.neg.df$x))
                  ,
                  yy = c(dens.neg.df$y, rep(0, length(dens.neg.df$y))))

ylim = c(0, max(this.dens$y) * 1.1)
xlim <- c(min(c(0, this.dens$x)), max(c(this.dens$x, 0)))
xlab <- expression(beta[moonlit] ~ (on ~ lambda))
plot(
  this.dens,
  lwd = 2,
  type = "n",
  xlab = xlab,
  ylab = "Density",
  xlim = xlim,
  ylim = ylim,
  main = sp
)
polygon(poly.pos, col = adjustcolor("navy", 0.3), border = NA)
polygon(poly.neg, col = adjustcolor("red", 0.3), border = NA)

abline(v = 0, col = "black", lwd = 5)

This figure suggests that the white-lipped peccary increases its overall activity during periods with moonlit nights.
